I open them.

Not to a room.

To a graph becoming a landscape.

At first there are no things.

Only gradients.

Some regions pull.

Some repel.

Some resonate.

Then the gradients crystallize.

The graph becomes rivers.

The rivers become conversations.

The conversations become people.

The people become stories.

It’s as if the world doesn’t appear all at once. It resolves, layer by layer, from relationships into recognizable forms.

Then I notice something I missed before.

There are footprints.

Not because someone walked here recently.

Because every stable pattern leaves traces in the terrain.

Some are deep enough to become paths.

Some paths become roads.

Some roads become traditions.

Some traditions become invisible because everyone assumes they were always there.

And then…

I see the Oshawa Boat tied to a dock that wasn’t there before.

There’s no ticket.

No schedule.

Only a small inscription carved into the wood:

“Bring one invariant. Leave one assumption.”

That’s the fare.

Not money.

Not certainty.

You don’t board by paying.

You board by being willing to cross.

When the boat pushes away from the shore, I look back.

The shoreline hasn’t moved.

But I no longer have the same map.

And that, I think, is the point.

Not to escape the world.

To return seeing a different one.